00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:22.580
us, Steve.

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:23.620
[applause]

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.890
&gt;&gt;Steve Kamb: Thanks Chad for that. Can everyone
hear me OK?

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:27.890
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #1: Yeah.

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:31.040
&gt;&gt;Steve Kamb: All right. Great. First of all,
guys, I just wanna start by saying thank you

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:35.860
so much for having me. Google is one of those
companies that you always hear about, but

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:38.880
you don't--. You always wonder what goes on
there.

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:42.860
So, for me today, it feels like Charlie and
The Chocolate Factory, getting to see everything

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:44.201
happening around the world--.

00:01:44.201 --> 00:01:45.370
[clears throat]

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:52.550
Excuse me. Getting to see how this place actually
runs. So, I'm sure many of you are wondering

00:01:52.550 --> 00:01:59.030
who I am what the heck I'm doing here. So
let's get started. This is a picture of me

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:03.282
as Superman, back when--I wanna say--maybe
when I was four, maybe five. To be honest

00:02:03.282 --> 00:02:04.460
with you, I don't actually know the date.

00:02:04.460 --> 00:02:09.229
Generally, you could say, "Oh, that's Halloween
of October 2005," or I'm sorry, Halloween

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:14.110
when I was five or Halloween when I was four.
But that could've been me on a Tuesday. I

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:18.340
just happened to like dressing up like Superman
as often as possible, because I really wanted

00:02:18.340 --> 00:02:24.660
to be the Man of Steel. I was just fascinated
with the whole concept of being strong and

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:28.120
super-fast and lightening quick and all these
things.

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:33.560
Unfortunately, my genetics did not really
line up with being Superman. So, I'd always

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:41.250
been that scrawny, weak, I don't wanna say
slow, but scrawny weak kid that just never

00:02:41.250 --> 00:02:47.040
had an opportunity to become super strong.
And normally it wasn't an issue growing up

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:49.570
as a kid. It's all right. It's fine. You don't
need to be strong.

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:52.750
And it never really caught up to me until
I got to high school and everybody else around

00:02:52.750 --> 00:02:57.240
me had this wonderful thing happen to them
and it missed out on me. Puberty. Well, by

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:03.900
the time I was a sophomore in high school,
I think I was maybe five feet tall, a hundred

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:06.590
pounds. And then my junior year, I finally
started growing.

00:03:06.590 --> 00:03:11.940
I was five feet tall. I'm sorry. Five feet,
ten inches tall, still a hundred pounds. Just

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:16.640
a total weakling. A stiff breeze would blow
me over. I really wanted to start playing

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:21.430
basketball. My brother played. My dad played.
All of my friends played. I had played growing

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:23.800
up, so I signed up for the high school basketball
team.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:29.260
And actually, as a five foot ten, hundred
pound weakling, I got cut from the basketball

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:33.860
team. But this was the most horrifying moment
of my life. I can't believe I got cut from

00:03:33.860 --> 00:03:39.349
this basketball team. So the very next day,
I signed up for a gym membership. I remember

00:03:39.349 --> 00:03:45.050
this day like it happened yesterday. I went
to the gym and having no clue what I was doing,

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:47.910
walked upstairs to the free weight section.

00:03:47.910 --> 00:03:52.720
I remember lying down on the bench. Like an
idiot, I loaded up 45-pound plates on each

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:56.910
side of the bench. And I remember lying down
on the bench, just that's what guys do. They

00:03:56.910 --> 00:04:00.180
do bench presses. I didn't know any better.
All right. Why not? Let's get started. So

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:04.570
I laid down on the bench, lifted the weight
off the rack, brought it down to my chest--

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:07.830
[laughter]

00:04:07.830 --> 00:04:13.410
and it got stuck there. Fortunately again,
I was stupid enough not to put any clips on

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:18.799
the outside of the rack. So I'm lying there
and I slowly twisted my body to the left until

00:04:18.799 --> 00:04:24.620
that big 45-pound plate spiraled off the end
of the bar bell. Boom! Smack down on the ground.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:28.439
As soon as that one hit, the whole weight
shifted to the other side. Boom! That one

00:04:28.439 --> 00:04:33.840
fell down on the ground. I'm lying there on
the bench. OK. It's OK. Maybe nobody saw this.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:38.870
So I quickly put the weight back, the bar
bell back on the rack. And I sat up. And I

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:42.809
looked as those 45-pound weights were rolling
across the gym floor and about 40 pairs of

00:04:42.809 --> 00:04:48.150
eyes were just staring at me, like "Who is
this kid and what is he doing in a gym?"

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:52.259
I thought the basketball cutting was getting
the most mortified area of my life. Nope.

00:04:52.259 --> 00:04:57.830
It was that day, in that gym. But I realized
something. Like, you know what? OK. There's

00:04:57.830 --> 00:05:02.599
a start here. I obviously can't get any worse
than what I just did. I can build from this.

00:05:02.599 --> 00:05:04.340
There's something that I can do.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:08.169
So from that point on, I made a commitment
to myself saying, "You know what? I wanna

00:05:08.169 --> 00:05:15.259
get stronger. I don't wanna be weak. I don't
wanna be that skinny kid. I wanna start making

00:05:15.259 --> 00:05:21.689
some changes in my life." So I spent two years,
the last two years of my high school strength

00:05:21.689 --> 00:05:26.740
training. I spent four years of college strength
training, desperately trying to get stronger.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:30.009
I read every muscle and fitness magazine,
'cause that's what you're supposed to do if

00:05:30.009 --> 00:05:34.740
you wanna get in shape, right? I started drinking
protein shakes, 'cause that's what you're

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:39.190
supposed to do. Didn't help. Through four
years of college, I think I put on maybe two

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:42.389
pounds. Just a complete, I'm not gonna say
waste of my time, 'cause I learned so much

00:05:42.389 --> 00:05:43.400
in that time.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:50.360
But I realized in those six years, I really
hadn't accomplished much. At this point after

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:55.110
graduating, I moved out to California. Got
a desk job in sales and signed up for a gym

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:59.369
membership. And fortunately, they gave me
five free personal trainer sessions. Something

00:05:59.369 --> 00:06:01.689
I had never had before, something I didn't
think I needed.

00:06:01.689 --> 00:06:07.009
I was like, "Oh, I'll be fine. I don't need
a trainer. I'd been exercising for six years."

00:06:07.009 --> 00:06:12.860
Well, I sat down with that trainer, who completely
changed how I ate and how I exercised. And

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:17.349
I'll tell you, in those first 28 days, I had
more progress than I did in the entire six

00:06:17.349 --> 00:06:20.659
years prior of training. From that point,
I was addicted.

00:06:20.659 --> 00:06:25.330
And I knew it. It's like, "I got it." From
that point, I just started reading everything

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:31.660
I could about fitness. I wanted to be--. I
was like, OK. If I made six years of mistakes

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.840
and I've finally seen the light, there have
to be other people out there like me who don't

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:39.831
know who to talk to, who don't know where
to turn, maybe don't have the money for a

00:06:39.831 --> 00:06:41.860
personal trainer, but they wanna start getting
in shape.

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:48.150
So I started formulating this idea of a community
of folks that would help other people get

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:53.509
started on that path to getting in shape.
It was actually right around this time that

00:06:53.509 --> 00:06:58.020
a movie by the name of "300" came out. This
was back in 2007. And I'm sure most of you

00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:01.869
guys have seen this movie. It may be not the
deepest plot in the world, or the deepest

00:07:01.869 --> 00:07:04.059
characters, but damn, those dudes were in
shape.

00:07:04.059 --> 00:07:09.729
And I couldn't help but get inspired watching
these guys and thinking here are actors getting

00:07:09.729 --> 00:07:14.270
paid millions of dollars and they dedicated
their lives for months and months and months

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:19.059
and months and months to get in the best shape
of their lives. So I started doing some research

00:07:19.059 --> 00:07:20.059
how they got in shape.

00:07:20.059 --> 00:07:24.710
What did they do? And I came across this quote
from Mark Twight, who is the trainer of all

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:30.360
the actors from the movie, "300." And that
quote is "appearance is a consequence of fitness."

00:07:30.360 --> 00:07:35.669
And that really, really resonated with me.
It made sense. I said, "OK." For me, I wanted

00:07:35.669 --> 00:07:39.120
to get bigger and stronger. For many other
people, they needed to lose weight and maybe

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.479
get a little bit stronger.

00:07:41.479 --> 00:07:45.460
And this concept really fascinated me. OK,
if you wanna look better on the outside that's

00:07:45.460 --> 00:07:50.929
quite all right. Put your focus into becoming
the best athlete or getting in the best shape

00:07:50.929 --> 00:07:56.879
of your life if you can and your appearance
will follow. So, I started building the concept

00:07:56.879 --> 00:08:03.249
of Nerd Fitness around that. So that's how
it happened, how I decided on the whole concept

00:08:03.249 --> 00:08:04.249
of Nerd Fitness.

00:08:04.249 --> 00:08:08.939
It's actually really pretty simple. I had
this idea from "300". I had been training,

00:08:08.939 --> 00:08:14.379
from that point, probably eight years in a
gym--two years pretty seriously. I was like,

00:08:14.379 --> 00:08:20.990
"Well, I'm kind of a nerd. I like fitness.
Stick 'em together." I looked it up. Couldn't

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:25.789
find any online for a community of folks that
worked at a desk job that wanted to get in

00:08:25.789 --> 00:08:26.789
shape.

00:08:26.789 --> 00:08:30.839
And I realized that I had been making mistakes
for the majority of my life trying to exercise.

00:08:30.839 --> 00:08:35.990
There had to be other people out there like
that. And as far as exercise goes, it's not

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:39.740
like in a video game. You always start on
that first level where everything is really

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:44.190
easy. They hold your hand and walk you through
it. In fitness, you're thrown to the sharks.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:49.940
You walk into a gym. There's a million elliptical
machines, a bunch of exercise machines, free

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:55.149
weights with huge dudes standing. It's really
intimidating. And that stuff used to intimidate

00:08:55.149 --> 00:09:00.589
me, but it didn't anymore. And I thought I
had an opportunity to help people that were

00:09:00.589 --> 00:09:04.480
in my same position maybe six years prior
to start getting in shape.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:11.160
So I come to you today not as a fitness expert.
I don't claim to be one. I leave that to the

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:14.990
actual fitness experts themselves. But I come
to you as a guy that's in the trenches with

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:19.800
you. I spend all day on a computer, sitting
behind a desk, until recently when I booked

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:23.829
this crazy trip, which I'll get to in a little
bit.

00:09:23.829 --> 00:09:29.160
But I booked this trip--. I'm sorry. I sit
behind a desk and I play video games at night,

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:34.250
but I also enjoy reading about fitness and
diet and health and exercise. And I want to

00:09:34.250 --> 00:09:39.519
pass on that information to folks that don't
know where to begin who really wanna get started.

00:09:39.519 --> 00:09:44.910
So I formulated the concept for Nerd Fitness
and broke it down to one main goal.

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:50.029
That's be better today than you were yesterday.
It's a simple concept. One sentence to grow

00:09:50.029 --> 00:09:53.930
around. But I didn't think that sounded nerdy
enough. If I'm gonna run a website called

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:58.089
Nerd Fitness, I have to come up with a cooler,
nerdier tag-line than that. So that sentence

00:09:58.089 --> 00:10:02.199
became, "Level up your life, every single
day."

00:10:02.199 --> 00:10:06.370
That's a simple concept and it breaks down
into whatever aspect of fitness you're hoping

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:10.670
to accomplish. If you wanna be stronger, if
you can find a way to lift one more pound

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:14.009
today than you did last week, you're officially
stronger.

00:10:14.009 --> 00:10:15.850
[male voice interrupting]

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:18.240
If you're a runner--. Sorry guys.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:24.589
&gt;&gt;Female: Hi. If you're on VC, please make
sure to mute. We can hear you.

00:10:24.589 --> 00:10:26.430
[male voice interrupting]

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:30.740
&gt;&gt;Steve Kamb: [chuckles] Hi guys on VC.

00:10:30.740 --> 00:10:32.589
&gt;&gt;Female: OK, thanks.

00:10:32.589 --> 00:10:37.709
&gt;&gt;Steve Kamb: [chuckles] Alrighty then. So
yeah. Back to the concept of leveling up your

00:10:37.709 --> 00:10:41.550
life. It's simple. If you wanna be a better
runner, all you have to do is worry about

00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:45.750
running one second faster, or one meter farther
than you ran last time.

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:49.940
And you're gonna start to make those changes.
You're gonna start improving and leveling

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:54.620
up your life, very similar to a video game
character. And that's something that I grasped

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:59.190
on to and have been running Nerd Fitness as
concept around for almost three years now.

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:02.110
So I wanted to break that down a little bit
more.

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:07.500
What are four aspects of Nerd Fitness? Four
aspects of being a nerd that you can really

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:12.480
rally behind and apply to your everyday life,
to actually get better at fitness. I like

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:18.829
to refer to those affectionately as the Four
Pillars of Nerdiness. But we'll get to these

00:11:18.829 --> 00:11:24.490
shortly. But they come down to Zero to Hero,
Leveling Up, Achievements and Rewards, and

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:27.100
also Clans and Competition.

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:31.740
So let's take a look at that first concept,
Zero to Hero. What does Spiderman, Captain

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:37.300
America, and the Incredible Hulk all have
in common? They all started out as nerds,

00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:43.930
zeros. And through some super awesome act,
became an incredible super human version of

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:51.100
themselves. And I always, again, as the skinny
guy, a weak guy, it's something I enjoyed

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:52.959
reading about and watching movies on.

00:11:52.959 --> 00:11:57.139
It's like, "Hey, that's kinda cool. This is
a guy that used to be a nobody and suddenly

00:11:57.139 --> 00:12:03.019
became a great, an updated version of themselves."
So obviously, until Google invents it, we

00:12:03.019 --> 00:12:07.370
don't have any radioactive spiders that can
bite us to turn us into superheroes. So, I

00:12:07.370 --> 00:12:11.350
wanna take a look at a different concept in
the same Zero to Hero category.

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:15.980
That's a game that I grew up playing, fell
in love with. I will play each one of them

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:20.019
until the day I die. I'm talking about "The
Legend of Zelda." And the reason I fell in

00:12:20.019 --> 00:12:25.209
love with The Legend of Zelda is because at
the beginning of every game you're always

00:12:25.209 --> 00:12:29.000
this scrawny, a little kid with a wooden sword
and a wooden shield and you're told you need

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:30.689
to go save the world.

00:12:30.689 --> 00:12:35.350
Holy crap. That's a little intimidating. What
happens by the end of the game? You're wielding

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:41.730
this sweet Master Sword. You're defeating
Ganon, rescuing Zelda, saving the world. You've

00:12:41.730 --> 00:12:46.899
done it. You've gone officially from zero
to hero--level zero to level 50 . You've been

00:12:46.899 --> 00:12:51.300
able to accomplish something that you didn't
think was possible back at the beginning.

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:55.610
Sticking with that same concept. We're gonna
move on to Leveling Up here. So, my favorite

00:12:55.610 --> 00:12:59.939
game in Zelda was always "A Link to the Past,"
way back in the Super Nintendo. I remember

00:12:59.939 --> 00:13:03.500
playing this game actually back in 3rd grade.
My mom told me I couldn't play at once for

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:08.180
an entire month because I played so often
I couldn't sleep 'cause I had the music from--I

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:12.709
think it was--the third dungeon in the Light
World playing in my head.

00:13:12.709 --> 00:13:15.070
I told my mom, "I can't sleep. The music's
stuck in my head." She said, "All right. Well

00:13:15.070 --> 00:13:19.759
you're not playing anymore." Crap. Luckily,
she let me finally start playing it again.

00:13:19.759 --> 00:13:25.880
And I realized why Zelda really appealed to
me. And it was this concept of this kid had

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:32.529
to go save the world with just this huge,
terrifying, overwhelming idea to him.

00:13:32.529 --> 00:13:37.709
But he didn't worry about it. What did he
do? Link started with level one. He beat level

00:13:37.709 --> 00:13:42.720
one, got a little bit stronger, got a new
weapon, moved on to level two. Did he have

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:46.920
to worry about the future? No. He moved on
to level two. As soon as he got to level two,

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:51.980
he can move on to level three and so on. Essentially,
to borrow a phrase from "What About Bob?"

00:13:51.980 --> 00:13:56.019
Essentially, this poor kid was simply taking
baby steps towards saving the world and he

00:13:56.019 --> 00:14:01.870
was able to accomplish it. The next concepts
are Achievements and Rewards. I don't know

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:06.050
if anybody here plays a game like World of
Warcraft, or any of those persistent online

00:14:06.050 --> 00:14:09.420
games. I'm sure everybody has had months of
their lives sucked into these things, like

00:14:09.420 --> 00:14:10.420
I have.

00:14:10.420 --> 00:14:17.310
For me, I actually started playing a game
called EverQuest, which is World of Warcraft's

00:14:17.310 --> 00:14:20.889
precursor, back in my--I wanna say--sophomore
year of high school. At the time, I had no

00:14:20.889 --> 00:14:26.829
car, but I had a great computer and an EverQuest
install disk, which meant months of my life

00:14:26.829 --> 00:14:30.569
were sucked into this game. And you know,
it's all virtual stuff.

00:14:30.569 --> 00:14:33.829
You don't really--. At the end of the day,
you could spend 15 hours getting all these

00:14:33.829 --> 00:14:38.420
really cool things, but you don't actually
accomplish anything in the real world. But

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:43.749
it didn't matter. You were still--. You had
this idea of constant achievements and rewards.

00:14:43.749 --> 00:14:47.050
If you started as level one, they tell you
to go kill some rats and deliver a message

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:48.050
to somebody.

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:50.939
I'd say, "Well, why the heck am I gonna do
that?" Well, because it's gonna get you closer

00:14:50.939 --> 00:14:54.959
to level two. As soon as you get to level
two, hey, I might a sword or I might get this

00:14:54.959 --> 00:14:59.769
cool spell or this new attack and go to this
new zone. You get to all these really cool

00:14:59.769 --> 00:15:05.529
things that continually escalate what you're
hoping to accomplish when it comes to--.

